{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d9424388-a032-4eec-9848-9d082f26f502","content":"Here's what breaks in each case under C# 15:\n\n---\n\n**1. SpanHelper.cs — Stricter ref-safety for span lifetimes**\n\n`[x * 2]` in a `Span<int>` uses implicit `stackalloc` whose lifetime is the loop body. Assigning it to `results` (which has method-wide scope) is a ref-safety violation — the stack memory is invalid after the iteration ends. C# 15 closes this hole.\n\n**Fix:** Use a `List<int>` or allocate outside the loop:\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Metadata.cs — `this` is invalid in attribute `nameof` context**\n\nC# 15 enforces that `this` is not available in attribute argument contexts (they're compile-time/static). `nameof` can still reference instance members directly — just not via `this`.\n\n**Fix:** Drop `this`:\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Pipeline.cs — `with` parsed as keyword in collection expressions**\n\nC# 15 expands `with`-expression parsing. Inside a collection expression `[...]`, the compiler now greedily parses `with(...)` as the start of a `with`-expression rather than a method call, causing a syntax error.\n\n**Fix:** Use a verbatim identifier to escape the keyword:\n```csharp\nobject @with(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\n\nOr simply rename the method to avoid the keyword collision entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed78b9d0-9996-4601-a813-4020c28b121f","outputTokens":446,"requestId":"C42A:5160:1D0B409:20E08CA:6A07C8D0"},"id":"27821b8f-9d9a-47e3-aed9-f1c28786ab55","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:31:05.646Z","parentId":"7e3a9cf6-e9a3-4732-9fa3-6a107df7a258"}
